%I A393444 #19 Apr 03 2026 01:45:06
%S A393444 3,0,8,7,8
%N A393444 Decimal expansion of Sum_{n >= 1} 1/A171397(prime(n)).
%C A393444 Start with the divergent series Sum_{n >= 1} 1/prime(n) and make it converge by replacing 1/prime(n) by 1/U(prime(n)), where U(k) means read k in base 10 and write it in base 11 (cf. A171397). The sum becomes 1/2 + 1/3 +1/5 + 1/7 + 1/12 + 1/14 + 1/18 + 1/20 + 1/25 + ..., which converges, albeit rather slowly.
%C A393444 Before Victor Miller's work, not a single digit of the value of the sum was known for certain. Hans Havermann had found that even after 10^12 terms the sum was about 2.94 and the leading digit was still uncertain (see "A Nasty Surprise ...").
%D A393444 Victor Miller, Summing a Challenging Series, Talk in Doron Zeilberger's Experimental Mathematics Seminar, Rutgers University, Apr 02 2026.
%H A393444 Victor Miller, <a href="https://sites.math.rutgers.edu/~zeilberg/expmath/miller26.pdf">A Difficult Prime Series Problem</a>, Slides for talk in Doron Zeilberger's Experimental Mathematics Seminar, Rutgers University, Apr 02 2026.
%H A393444 N. J. A. Sloane, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3RAYoaKMckM">A Nasty Surprise in a Sequence and Other OEIS Stories</a>, Experimental Mathematics Seminar, Rutgers University, Oct 10 2024, Youtube video; <a href="https://sites.math.rutgers.edu/~zeilberg/expmath/sloane85BD.pdf">Slides</a> [Mentions this sequence in slides 13-27]
%H A393444 Doron Zeilberger, <a href="https://sites.math.rutgers.edu/~zeilberg/expmath/">Homepage for Experimental Mathematics Seminar</a>.
%e A393444 The sum is 3.0878... Victor Miller shows that the value lies in the interval (3.0878725218714846, 3.0878855128344616).
%Y A393444 Cf. A171397, A375805.
%K A393444 nonn,cons,base,more,new
%O A393444 1,1
